3. Streams API

What is a Stream?

A Stream processes collections in a declarative manner.

Traditional Approach

List<String> results =
        new ArrayList<>();
for(String name : names) {
    if(name.startsWith("J")) {
        results.add(name);
    }
}

Stream Approach

List<String> results =
        names.stream()
             .filter(name -> name.startsWith("J"))
             .toList();

⸻

Filter

customers.stream()
         .filter(Customer::isActive)
         .forEach(System.out::println);

⸻

Map

customers.stream()
         .map(Customer::getName)
         .forEach(System.out::println);

⸻

Sorted

customers.stream()
         .sorted(
             Comparator.comparing(
                 Customer::getName))
         .forEach(System.out::println);

⸻

Collect

List<String> names =
        customers.stream()
                 .map(Customer::getName)
                 .toList();

⸻

Parallel Streams

customers.parallelStream()
         .forEach(System.out::println);

Use Case

Large datasets and CPU-intensive processing.

⸻

Top Java Stream Interview Question

Find Second Largest Distinct Number

int secondLargest =
        Arrays.stream(nums)
              .distinct()
              .boxed()
              .sorted((a, b) -> b - a)
              .skip(1)
              .findFirst()
              .orElseThrow();

Complexity

Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(n)

